Page 1: Domain Name System (DNS) Overview
DNS: Domain Name System
Definition: DNS is a system that converts domain names into IP addresses.
Purpose: Humans cannot remember all the application IP addresses required when the internet and machine network communicate. Every system has its own unique IP address.
The Problem: While we know names like google.com, youtube.com, or amazon.com, the internet communicates via IP addresses.
The Core Idea: Without DNS, you would have to remember a number like 142.250.193.14. Since these numbers are hard to remember, a DNS conversion is performed.
Workflow: Whenever a user enters a URL (e.g., www.google.com), it first goes to the DNS server and then eventually to the target web server.

