Page 4: DNS Caching & Server Types
DNS Caching:
To make the internet faster, DNS results are cached temporarily.
TTL (Time to Live): This mapping is handled by TTL; once it expires, the DNS must resolve the address again.
Note: This entire cycle happens in the "blink of an eye".
Types of DNS Servers:
Root DNS Server: The top level of the DNS hierarchy that directs queries to TLD servers.
Top Level Domain (TLD) Server: Handles domain endings like .com, .org, .edu, and .in.
Authoritative Server: Stores the actual domain-to-IP mapping (Example: amazon.com → 205.251.242.103).
Implementation Note: Authoritative servers have this data because whenever a domain is bought, the owner registers the domain name into it.